{
  "texts": [
    "Even identical words can convey diverse meanings based on their order.",
    "Consequently, two challenges require resolution.First, when examining word correlations, large language models primarily focus on the statistical likelihood of word combinations co-occurring within the training corpus.",
    "This approach tends to overlook the inherent semantic, grammatical, and word order intricacies present within the sentence itself.",
    "Indeed, interchanging the positions of two identical words can lead to distinct semantic interpretations, for exam-ple, be f ore long and long be f ore are two phrases with different meanings.Second, owing to the memory constraints inherent in transformer models when handling lengthy texts, utilizing transformer-based models might not be optimal for expressing text semantics.",
    "This is particularly evident in their insensitivity toward sentences containing negative words, such as \"no,\" despite the remarkable accomplishments these models have achieved in classification tasks [32]."
  ]
}